'''Thermal emittance''' or '''thermal emissivity''' is the ratio of the [[radiant emittance]] of [[heat]] of a specific object or surface to that of a standard [[black body]]. Emissivity and emittivity are both [[dimensionless quantities]] given in the range of 0 to 1, but [[emissivity]] refers to a [[material property]] (of a homogeneous material), while emittivity refers to specific samples or objects.

For building products, thermal emittance measurements are taken for wavelengths in the [[infrared]]. Determining the thermal emittance and [[solar reflectance]] of building materials, especially [[roofing]] materials, can be very useful for reducing heating and cooling [[energy accounting|energy costs]] in buildings. Combined index Solar Reflectance Index (SRI) is often used to determine the overall ability to reflect solar heat and release thermal heat. A roofing surface with high solar reflectance and high thermal emittance will reflect solar heat and release absorbed heat readily. High thermal emittance material radiates thermal heat back into the atmosphere more-readily than one with a low thermal emittance. 

