In [[optics]] the '''noise-equivalent flux density (NEFD)''' or '''noise-equivalent irradiance (NEI)''' of a system is the level of [[flux]] density required to be equivalent to the [[Signal noise|noise]] present in the system.<ref>{{cite book |title=Physical Optics and Light Measurements |last=Malacara |first=Daniel |page=247 |year=1988 |publisher=[[Academic Press]] |isbn=9780124759718 }}</ref> It is a measure used by astronomers in determining the accuracy of observations.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Benford | first1 = D. J. | last2 = Hunter | first2 = T. R. | last3 = Phillips | first3 = T. G. | title = Noise Equivalent Power of Background Limited Thermal Detectors at Submillimeter Wavelengths| journal = International Journal of Infrared and Millimeter Waves | volume = 19 | issue = 7 | pages = 931 | year = 1998 | doi = 10.1023/A:1022671223858 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>

The NEFD can be related to a light detector's [[Noise-equivalent power]] for a collection area ''A'' and a photon bandwidth <math>\nu</math> by:

<math>NEFD = \eta \frac{NEP}{A \nu}</math>, where a factor <math>\eta</math> (often 2, in the case of switching between measuring a source and measuring off-source) accounts for the photon statistics for the mode of operation.

