{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}} {{for|the curvature form|Field strength (theoretical physics)}}
In [[physics]], '''field strength''' or '''intensity''' means the [[magnitude (mathematics)|magnitude]] of a [[vector (geometry)|vector]]-valued [[field (physics)|field]]. For example, [[electromagnetic field]] results in both [[electric field strength]] and [[magnetic field strength]]. As an application, in [[radio frequency]] [[telecommunications]], the '''[[signal strength]]''' excites a receiving antenna and thereby induce a voltage at a specific frequency and polarization in order to provide an input signal to a radio receiver. [[Field strength meter]]<nowiki/>s are used for such applications as cellular, broadcasting, wi-fi and a wide variety of other radio-related applications. <!-- Magnetic Field intensity is expressed as H; its usual unit is amperes/meter, A/m, A-turn/m, A-t/m. Magnetic field intensity is equal TO B/u, Where 'B' is magnetic flux density and 'u' is permeability of the medium.--->
